<main>

<section id="before">
  <h2><span class="num">01</span>Let's get started</h2>
  <p class="sub">Three quick things to knock out right now so we can get straight to the good stuff.</p>
  <div class="card">
    <h3>1 · Create a free account</h3>
    <p>If you don't already have one, sign up for either:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="https://claude.ai" target="_blank">claude.ai</a> (what I'll be demoing)</li>
      <li><a href="https://chat.openai.com" target="_blank">chat.openai.com</a> (ChatGPT — works just as well for today)</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Email or Google sign-up. The free tier is all we need.</p>
    <h3>2 · What you need today</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Your laptop (charged)</li>
      <li>This link: <em>[Emily will share in the room]</em></li>
      <li>An internet connection</li>
    </ul>
    <h3>3 · Quickly, before we begin — jot down</h3>
    <p>Grab paper, your phone, whatever's handy, and scribble out:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>3–5 projects you're actively working on (work, personal, family — anything)</li>
      <li>5–10 things you're trying to get done this week</li>
      <li>2–3 things you're waiting on from other people</li>
      <li>One sentence about what matters most to you right now</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Rough is fine. Messy is fine. You'll turn this into your Personal Productivity Tracker during the exercise.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="callout">
    <strong>No pro plan required.</strong> The free tier handles everything we're doing today.
  </div>
</section>

<section id="flow">
  <h2><span class="num">02</span>Today's Agenda</h2>
  <p class="sub">Interrupt anytime — I'm yours for the hour. No dumb questions, no wrong reactions. Here's what we'll cover:</p>
  <div class="timeline">
    <div class="step">
      <div class="title">Welcome</div>
      <div class="desc">Why you're here. What you want to walk out knowing.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="title">What is AI?</div>
      <div class="desc">A plain-English mental model for how large language models actually work.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="title">The AI landscape</div>
      <div class="desc">Who the major players are, what each is known for, and what they can actually do.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="title">How to spot use cases</div>
      <div class="desc">A few simple questions to ask yourself to figure out where AI can save you time or brainpower.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="title">Common concerns</div>
      <div class="desc">Privacy, hallucinations, kids, and the stuff AI still can't do.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="title">Hands-on activity</div>
      <div class="desc">Build your own Personal Productivity Tracker with Claude.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="tools">
  <h2><span class="num">03</span>The AI landscape</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="https://www.theneuron.ai/top-tools/" target="_blank">The Neuron's Top AI Tools</a> — a constantly-updated, categorized directory of what's worth using right now.</li>
    <li><a href="https://you.com/home" target="_blank">You.com</a> — a meta-search that lets you compare answers across multiple AI models side-by-side.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>The World of AI Features</h3>
  <p>The category "AI" is too broad. What matters is which <em>features</em> a tool supports, because that's how you match it to a use case.</p>
  <div class="features">
    <div class="feat"><span class="feat-name">Chat</span><span class="feat-desc">Back-and-forth conversation, brainstorming, explaining, summarizing.</span></div>
    <div class="feat"><span class="feat-name">Coding</span><span class="feat-desc">Writing, debugging, and explaining code.</span></div>
    <div class="feat"><span class="feat-name">Document iteration</span><span class="feat-desc">Drafting, editing, and revising long docs across multiple rounds.</span></div>
    <div class="feat"><span class="feat-name">Data analysis</span><span class="feat-desc">Uploading spreadsheets/CSVs and asking questions of your data.</span></div>
    <div class="feat"><span class="feat-name">Image gen &amp; editing</span><span class="feat-desc">Create images from text; edit or extend existing images.</span></div>
    <div class="feat"><span class="feat-name">Workflow automation</span><span class="feat-desc">Triggers and actions that run without you ("when X, do Y").</span></div>
    <div class="feat"><span class="feat-name">Tool use / API calls</span><span class="feat-desc">AI reaches out to other software on your behalf.</span></div>
    <div class="feat"><span class="feat-name">Voice mode</span><span class="feat-desc">Speak to the AI, or have it read aloud to you.</span></div>
    <div class="feat"><span class="feat-name">Transcription</span><span class="feat-desc">Convert audio or meetings into searchable text.</span></div>
    <div class="feat"><span class="feat-name">Vibecoding</span><span class="feat-desc">Build working software from a plain-English description.</span></div>
    <div class="feat"><span class="feat-name">Research + citations</span><span class="feat-desc">Answers grounded in sources you can click and verify.</span></div>
    <div class="feat"><span class="feat-name">Deep reasoning</span><span class="feat-desc">Model takes longer and works harder on hard problems.</span></div>
    <div class="feat"><span class="feat-name">Agents / computer use</span><span class="feat-desc">AI takes multi-step actions on its own.</span></div>
  </div>

  <h3>Questions to ask when vetting a new AI tool</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>What am I actually trying to do? (chat, create, analyze, automate, search…)</li>
    <li>Which of the features above does it support — and which does it do <em>best</em>?</li>
    <li>Where does my data live, and does this tool need access to it?</li>
    <li>How private or sensitive is my input? What does the provider do with it?</li>
    <li>Do I need sources I can verify, or is a confident answer enough?</li>
    <li>Do I want it to <em>tell</em> me something, or <em>do</em> something for me?</li>
    <li>How often will I use it — once, weekly, daily? (Daily-use tools are worth paying for; one-offs aren't.)</li>
    <li>What's the free tier, and what unlocks with paid?</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>The main tools, by what they're best at</h3>
  <div class="grid grid-2">
    <div class="tool">
      <div class="tag">Today's demo</div>
      <h4>Claude · <a href="https://claude.ai" target="_blank">claude.ai</a></h4>
      <p><strong>Best for:</strong> document iteration, vibecoding, thoughtful writing, long-context work, deep reasoning.</p>
      <p><em>Artifacts</em> give you a live preview of HTML/code/docs beside the chat — which is why it's our pick for today's tracker build.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="tool">
      <div class="tag">Most well-known</div>
      <h4>ChatGPT · <a href="https://chat.openai.com" target="_blank">chat.openai.com</a></h4>
      <p><strong>Best for:</strong> chat, voice mode, image generation (DALL·E), data analysis, agents (Operator on paid).</p>
      <p>The broadest feature set in one place. Similar day-to-day feel to Claude; a bit more multimodal out of the box.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="tool">
      <div class="tag">Built into Google</div>
      <h4>Gemini · <a href="https://gemini.google.com" target="_blank">gemini.google.com</a></h4>
      <p><strong>Best for:</strong> research with live search, anything touching Gmail / Docs / Calendar, image generation (Imagen), Android.</p>
      <p>The default choice if your life already lives inside Google Workspace.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="tool">
      <div class="tag">Built into Office</div>
      <h4>Copilot · <a href="https://copilot.microsoft.com" target="_blank">copilot.microsoft.com</a></h4>
      <p><strong>Best for:</strong> document iteration inside Word, data analysis inside Excel, email drafting in Outlook, meetings in Teams.</p>
      <p>Lives inside the apps you're already in. The default choice if you're a Microsoft 365 shop.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="tool">
      <div class="tag">Research</div>
      <h4>Perplexity · <a href="https://www.perplexity.ai" target="_blank">perplexity.ai</a></h4>
      <p><strong>Best for:</strong> research with citations, current events, fact-finding, shopping comparisons.</p>
      <p>Every answer comes with linked sources. The go-to when you care more about <em>where the answer came from</em> than the prose.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="tool">
      <div class="tag">Images &amp; video</div>
      <h4>Midjourney, DALL·E, Sora, Runway</h4>
      <p><strong>Best for:</strong> image generation &amp; editing, video generation, creative direction.</p>
      <p>Different category from chat tools. Great for marketing, slides, social, creative projects.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="tool">
      <div class="tag">Transcription</div>
      <h4>Otter, Fathom, Granola, Fireflies</h4>
      <p><strong>Best for:</strong> transcription, meeting notes, searchable recordings.</p>
      <p>These plug into Zoom / Meet / Teams and turn your calls into text you can actually find later.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="tool">
      <div class="tag">Automation</div>
      <h4>Zapier, Make, n8n</h4>
      <p><strong>Best for:</strong> workflow automation, tool use / API calls, agents.</p>
      <p>These aren't chat tools — they're the wiring that connects AI to the rest of your software (email, calendar, CRM, Slack, etc.).</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="exercise">
  <h2><span class="num">04</span>Personal Productivity Tracker</h2>
  <p class="sub">A single HTML file that tracks your tasks with real structure — task, description, due date, next step, status — all in one place, saved to your browser, editable inline.</p>

  <h3>What you're building</h3>
  <div class="dash-preview">
    <h5>▾ Active projects</h5>
    <div class="task">
