    </div>
    <div class="task">
      <div class="task-row"><div class="box"></div><span class="task-name">Draft offsite agenda v1</span><span class="task-due">Today</span><span class="task-status status-inprogress">In progress</span></div>
      <div class="task-meta"><span><strong>Next step:</strong> Outline 4 blocks for day one.</span></div>
    </div>
    <h5>▾ Waiting on</h5>
    <div class="task">
      <div class="task-row"><div class="box"></div><span class="task-name">Legal review — vendor contract</span><span class="task-due">Asked Mon</span><span class="task-status status-waiting">Priya</span></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>The columns</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Task</strong> — the thing to do.</li>
    <li><strong>Description</strong> — one line of context so future-you remembers what this is.</li>
    <li><strong>Due date</strong> — when it has to happen (or "someday" for backlog).</li>
    <li><strong>Next step</strong> — the very next tiny action, so you never hit a wall.</li>
    <li><strong>Status</strong> — Not started / In progress / Blocked / Waiting on / Done.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>How to build it</h3>
  <ol class="steps">
    <li><strong>Open Claude (or ChatGPT).</strong> Paste the starter prompt below.</li>
    <li><strong>Upload your existing to-dos</strong> — the napkin list you just jotted down, a screenshot of your email inbox, a meeting notes doc, a Word doc of goals, anything you've got. The LLM will auto-populate the tracker with real items from your life.</li>
    <li><strong>Customize it.</strong> Tell the LLM: change the colors, add your name, rename sections, add a habit tracker at the bottom, whatever feels good.</li>
    <li><strong>Ask for a downloadable HTML file.</strong> Say "give me the final file as a downloadable HTML I can save to my computer."</li>
    <li><strong>Open it in your browser.</strong> Double-click the file. Your tracker is live. Bookmark it.</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Starter prompt</h3>
  <div class="copy-wrap">
    <button class="copy-btn" data-copy="starter">Copy starter prompt</button>
<pre id="starter">Build me a single-file HTML personal productivity tracker. It should be a living document I can keep open in a browser tab and actually use every day.

Each task has five columns:
- Task (short name)
- Description (one line of context)
- Due date
- Next step (the very next tiny action)
- Status (Not Started / In Progress / Blocked / Waiting On / Done)

Group tasks into collapsible sections:
1. Active projects
2. This week
3. Today
4. Waiting on
5. Backlog / Someday

Requirements:
- All data autosaves to localStorage so it persists when I close the tab.
- Everything is inline-editable: click any field to edit it.
- Each section has a "+ add task" button; each task has a delete (×) button on hover.
- Status is a dropdown with color-coded pills.
- Overdue due dates show in red; due today shows in the accent color.
- At the top: today's date, an "X of Y done today" stat, and a progress bar.
- Sections are collapsible; remember collapsed state.
- Buttons for Export JSON, Import JSON, and Reset (with confirm).

Design:
- Warm, calm palette. Cream background, deep ink text, one rust/terracotta accent.
- Rounded corners, generous whitespace, system font stack.
- Feels like a Moleskine, not a spreadsheet.

No dependencies. All inline CSS and JS. Make this something I'd want to keep open all the time.

I'll paste or upload my existing to-dos, emails, or notes below — please pre-populate the tracker with real items from those. Ask me for anything you need.</pre>
  </div>

  <div class="callout warn">
    <strong>Heads up.</strong> Inside Claude's Artifact preview, the "save to browser" part may not work fully — that's a preview-sandbox quirk. The tracker becomes fully functional once you download the HTML file and open it from your computer.
  </div>

  <h3>Want to take it further? Pro-version ideas</h3>
  <p>These are things you can't build in the 15 minutes we have today, but they're all doable with a little setup:</p>
  <div class="grid grid-2">
    <div class="card">
      <h4>Desktop file sync</h4>
      <p>Save the tracker to a folder that syncs (iCloud, Dropbox, OneDrive). Open it from any device — same data everywhere. Pair with something like <a href="https://obsidian.md" target="_blank">Obsidian</a> if you want the same idea in markdown.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h4>Weekly trigger email</h4>
      <p>Use <a href="https://zapier.com" target="_blank">Zapier</a> or <a href="https://make.com" target="_blank">Make</a> to email you every Sunday with a prompt: "paste your tracker state here, I'll do a weekly review." Your inbox becomes the ritual.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h4>Calendar events</h4>
      <p>Ask the LLM to add a "Send to calendar" button that generates a <code>.ics</code> file from any task with a due date. One click → the task lives on your Google/Outlook calendar.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h4>Ask Claude button</h4>
      <p>Add a button that copies your current state to the clipboard and opens claude.ai. Paste, ask for prioritization, a weekly review, or a "what am I avoiding?" nudge.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

